after thinking about it that last post may still be a bit obscure.

if the bot were given the ability to &quot;stick&quot; to a wall and follow it around one of the things you might want to give the bot is the ability to avoid crashing. Crashing being death you have mutually exclusive things that can happen. crash or finish. It seems reasonable to me to give the bot that knowledge right up front. 
It has proximity sensors(I assume the yellow lines are not ray guns...) and we know crashing will never provide us with a desired result.
Now, the bot can map the maze by following the wall. 

Well, by exhaustively traversing the maze it will always find the red dot on the first pass. 

Great, so what&#39;s the point of trying to &quot;learn&quot; what can be done with exhaustive search?

This connects the dots for what Ken has been saying about domains providing &quot;acceptable behaviors&quot; that limit the novelty.
In this case the solution will be novel every time you move the dot or change the maze but the bot will still find the dot on the first generation.
We have thus restricted the novelty to the point that AI is actually pointless.
Now push that into a 3,4, or 5 dimensional space.

By &quot;properly&quot; identifying and supplying these &quot;domain acceptable behaviors&quot; any space should be manageable.

hopefully that made a bit more sense.






